#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:5
msgid "Tutorial: Reconstructing a Design from an STL"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:7
msgid "This tutorial describes a practical workflow for using :func:`~build123d.detect_primitives` to help reconstruct a parametric build123d model from an STL mesh."
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:11
msgid "This is not a push-button STL-to-CAD converter. It is a mesh-guided redesign process. The goal is to extract enough analytic structure from a triangulated model to make manual reconstruction faster and more reliable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:17
msgid "Rebuilding a design from STL is usually slow, approximate, and manual. STL files contain triangles, not modeling intent. Even when :func:`~build123d.detect_primitives` finds useful planes, cylinders, and spheres, the final build123d model still needs to be designed deliberately."
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:22
msgid "Before working through this tutorial, review Steps 1-3 of :ref:`design_tutorial`. The same ideas apply here:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:25
msgid "identify planes of symmetry"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:26
msgid "identify likely axes of rotation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:27
msgid "choose a convenient origin before doing any serious work"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:29
msgid "These preparation steps often reduce the amount of mesh that needs to be reconstructed to one half, one quarter, or even less."
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:33
msgid "Overview"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:35
msgid "The workflow described here is:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:37
msgid "Import the STL with :class:`~mesher.Mesher`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:38
msgid "Split the mesh by symmetry planes and isolate the region to redesign."
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:39
msgid "Save that reduced mesh section as a BREP file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:40
msgid "Reload the BREP section while iterating on reconstruction."
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:41
msgid "Run :func:`~build123d.detect_primitives`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:42
msgid "Inspect the returned primitives, leftovers, and generated code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:43
msgid "Rebuild the design intentionally from those clues."
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:45
msgid "The key output of ``detect_primitives`` is guidance:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:47
msgid "``primitives`` shows what was recognized analytically"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:48
msgid "``leftovers`` shows what was not covered"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:49
msgid "``code_lines`` provides algebra-mode fragments that often reveal common planes and likely sketch structure"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:53
msgid "Why Cache a Working Section as BREP?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:55
msgid "Importing STL with :class:`~mesher.Mesher` is convenient, but large meshes can be slow to load and process. Once a useful section of the part has been isolated, save it as a BREP file and use that for repeated experimentation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:59
msgid "BREP files reload much more efficiently in build123d and are better suited to an iterative reconstruction script."
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:63
msgid "Preparing the Mesh"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:65
msgid "Start with the STL import and isolate the smallest useful section of the part."
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:80
msgid "The exact planes depend on the part. The point is not to begin running ``detect_primitives`` on the full mesh if symmetry can remove most of the work."
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:84
msgid "Reconstruction Script"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:86
msgid "Once the mesh section has been cached as BREP, iterate on a separate script or enable a reconstruction section of the same script with a Boolean switch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:99
msgid "This call returns three complementary outputs:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:101
msgid "``primitives``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:102
msgid "A :class:`~topology.ShapeList` of analytic faces that were recognized from the mesh. These are typically planes, cylinders, and spheres. Planar primitives are returned as rectangles sized to the planar region's bounding box, not as the original tessellated mesh patch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:107
msgid "``leftovers``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:108
msgid "Mesh faces that were not matched by the primitive detectors. These indicate freeform regions, noisy regions, or places where manual work is still required."
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:112
msgid "``code_lines``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:113
msgid "Generated algebra-mode code corresponding to the recognized primitives."
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:116
msgid "Inspecting the Results"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:118
msgid "The inspection step is the heart of this workflow."
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:121
msgid "1. Examine the primitives visually"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:123
msgid "Look at the returned ``primitives`` and decide what the detector found well."
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:125
msgid "Useful questions include:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:127
msgid "Are the expected planar faces present?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:128
msgid "Do fillets appear as cylinders?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:129
msgid "Do rounded corners appear as spheres?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:130
msgid "Are repeated features recognized consistently?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:132
msgid "In a simple mechanical part, good output often consists of a small number of common planes, repeated cylinders with similar radii, and only a few leftovers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:136
msgid "2. Examine the leftovers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:138
msgid "``leftovers`` show what still needs manual interpretation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:140
msgid "Large leftover regions often indicate one of three things:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:142
msgid "the part contains geometry that is not well approximated by planes, cylinders, or spheres"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:144
msgid "the mesh is noisy or irregular"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:145
msgid "the working section is still too large to interpret comfortably"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:147
msgid "If too much of the mesh appears in ``leftovers``, it may be better to refine the working section, identify more symmetry, or redesign that area manually instead of trying to automate it further."
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:152
msgid "3. Examine the generated code"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:154
msgid "The generated ``code_lines`` are intentionally written in Algebra mode and use ``Plane * Pos`` structure to make repeated placement patterns easier to spot."
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:157
msgid "This often helps answer questions such as:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:159
msgid "which faces lie on the same construction plane?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:160
msgid "which circles belong to the same sketch?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:161
msgid "which cylindrical or spherical regions are repeated instances of one feature?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:163
msgid "Treat this code as an annotated report, not necessarily as the final model."
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:165
msgid "For planar parts in particular, the generated lines are often naturally grouped by plane. A sequence such as ``Plane.XY.offset(...)`` with a few repeated offset values usually indicates related structure that may belong to one sketch or one construction stage."
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:171
msgid "Worked Example: Filleted Box"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:173
msgid "As a controlled example, consider a filleted box:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:179
msgid "Running ``detect_primitives`` on this geometry produces output like:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:210
msgid "This output is informative in several ways:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:212
msgid "the six box faces appear as rectangles on three principal planes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:213
msgid "the edge fillets appear as cylinders grouped around those same planes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:214
msgid "the corner blends appear as spheres near the eight cube corners"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:216
msgid "The generated code is also structured by plane:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:218
msgid "``Plane.XY.offset(...)`` appears with three distinct offsets"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:219
msgid "``Plane.YZ.offset(...)`` appears with three distinct offsets"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:220
msgid "``Plane.ZX.offset(...)`` appears with three distinct offsets"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:222
msgid "That organization is often more useful than any one primitive by itself because it suggests how the model could be regrouped into sketches and construction steps."
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:226
msgid "Although this output is correct and useful, it still does not represent the best final build123d model. The original design intent is much simpler:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:233
msgid "That is a good example of the main lesson of this tutorial: the generated code helps reveal structure, but the final model should usually be rewritten in a cleaner, higher-level form."
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:238
msgid "Turning Primitive Hints into Sketches"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:240
msgid "Once repeated planes become obvious in ``code_lines``, start grouping related features into sketches and features of your own."
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:243
msgid "For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:245
msgid "several rectangles on ``Plane.XY`` may indicate one base sketch and one or more extrusions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:247
msgid "repeated circles on one plane may indicate hole or boss locations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:248
msgid "a collection of cylinders with the same radius may indicate that a fillet or round was part of the original design intent"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:251
msgid "The generated code is often most useful when treated as:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:253
msgid "a list of candidate construction planes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:254
msgid "a list of likely sketch elements"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:255
msgid "a list of repeated primitive sizes and placements"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:258
msgid "Signs of Good Output"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:260
msgid "``detect_primitives`` is most helpful when:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:262
msgid "the mesh is reasonably clean"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:263
msgid "the part is mostly mechanical"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:264
msgid "many surfaces are planar, cylindrical, or spherical"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:265
msgid "there are clear planes of symmetry or repeated features"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:267
msgid "In these cases, primitives and generated code often cluster into obvious reconstruction steps."
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:271
msgid "Signs of Poor Output"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:273
msgid "Expect more manual work when:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:275
msgid "the mesh contains freeform surfaces"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:276
msgid "the STL is noisy or heavily tessellated"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:277
msgid "the part has no obvious symmetry"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:278
msgid "many important regions remain in ``leftovers``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:279
msgid "the generated code contains many tiny or redundant fragments"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:281
msgid "When this happens, it may be faster to use the mesh only as a visual reference and rebuild the part manually from dimensions and intent."
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:285
msgid "Summary"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:287
msgid "The STL reconstruction workflow in build123d is:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:289
msgid "analyze the part as a designer, not as a mesh processor"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:290
msgid "isolate the smallest useful region with symmetry and splitting"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:291
msgid "cache that region as BREP"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:292
msgid "run :func:`~build123d.detect_primitives`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:293
msgid "inspect primitives, leftovers, and code"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:294
msgid "rebuild the part intentionally in build123d"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_stl_reconstruction.rst:296
msgid "The most useful mindset is to treat ``detect_primitives`` as a design assistant. It can show where the planes, cylinders, and spheres probably are, but the final parametric model still comes from careful human interpretation."
msgstr ""
